About
Buckingham Palace is recognised around the world as the focus of national and royal celebrations as well as the backdrop to the regular Changing the Guard ceremony. Explore the magnificent State Rooms which are open to visitors for 10 weeks each summer and on selected dates during winter and spring. During a visit to Buckingham Palace, visitors can see the 19 magnificent State Rooms, which provide the setting for ceremonial occasions and official entertaining. All rooms are furnished with many of the greatest treasures from the Royal Collection.
Duration: 2-3 hours

The area

Address
Neighborhood: Westminster
If you only had an afternoon to experience London on a grand scale, Westminster would be a wise place to start. The ornate Houses of Parliament and Westminster Abbey sit adjacent at a corner of Parliament Square, and a short stroll along The Mall leads to Buckingham Palace. Trafalgar Square and Nelson's Column are just up the road as well. As captivating as the architecture is, the wonders of Mother Nature are highlights of the area too. St James's Park (arguably London's loveliest), the expansive Green Park, and pedestrian friendly tree lined paths along the river showcase the exquisite manicure provided by English gardeners. Just beyond the landmarks and the gorgeous outdoor spaces, quiet residential squares and age old local pubs offer a more subdued take on this global seat of power in the heart of London.
How to get there
  • Green Park • 8 min walk
  • Hyde Park Corner • 10 min walk

History of Royalty
Oct 2024 • Family
Going to go ahead with five stars although I was thinking 4 1/2. I was comparing the tour in my head to the tour of Windsor Castle. Saw a lot more decorative items on display at Windsor. A huge entire room of stunning gifts from heads of governments around the world. An absolute treasure room!
Obviously the Buckingham state rooms were gorgeous especially the architectural details, ceilings, floors, furniture and stunning art work. You just have to imagine the history, the meetings and all the glamour of significant events. Some of the rooms seemed empty to the best of my memory or because of the crowds.
Extremely disappointed with the no photography rule. The two things that stood out to me were an obvious lack of Queen Elizabeth paintings etc - even though there were several, I expected more. The other thing was the display of King Charles newly unveiled and controversial portrait - I had seen photographs of it but seeing it in person was mesmerizing! Something about the eyes - they were piercing! Great capture by the artist. Stand close to experience it.
Be prepared for lots of walking and standing - when you realize you have gone through probably less than a fourth of the palace you will be astonished. Do they really walk this far on a daily basis? There is a nice gift shop as the end and rest rooms. Then you will continue on a very long walk to the exit which will be quite a ways from where you entered.

Berthoud, CO1,003 contributions
Only open specific times during the year.
Sep 2024 • Friends
The State Rooms are the public rooms in the Palace where the monarch and members of the Royal Family receive and entertain guests on State, ceremonial and official occasions. They are in the style of 1825, when they were created, and have some of the finest English and French furniture in the world, along with world renown paintings. Some of our favorite rooms were the Throne Room, the White Room, the Picture Gallery and the Grand Staircase. You exit by walking through the Palace Gardens, where there is a café and an ice cream shop.

Have Camera, Will Travel
South Bend, IN3,752 contributions
The Tour was amazing.
Aug 2024 • Couples
My partner and I did the Buckingham Palace Tour on a wet Saturday Morning in August. Once we decided to go back to London, it is the first ticket I booked (5 or 6 months in advance). I know it is a hard one to get, so booked it as soon as I could and planned the rest of the trip around out time, which was 10AM (arrived at 9:30am).

It was a bummer that no pictures were allowed as I take pictures of everything, but being able to just take in each room was nice. The throne room was not nearly as extravagant as I was expecting, but really interesting to see. The Dining Area, the Music Room and the Ballroom were all favorites. We even danced for a few seconds in the Ballroom!

We exited and went to the café they have set up for a few snacks and water. Then on the the store they have set up towards the garden. I really loved some of the tea sets and tea cups, but they were a bit out of my budget for something I will probably never use at home. I still ended up with 5 or 6 things to bring home (and a Union Jack umbrella for the moment).

The rain did dampen the garden area, so we pretty much headed to the exit on the other side of the garden. It is a memorable tour and I highly recommend it.
